@node "tour" "Tour"
@next "window"
@prev "MUI"
Welcome to the guided tour of Convertor! If you opened this guide from Convertor, put its window near this guide, otherwise start it.
Look the @{"User Interface" link window} for more information about the gadgets on the windows.
We'll start with some easy operation, and then increase complexity.
Note: don't get frightened by this huge amount of text, you can stop when you want, it is not required to fully read this chapter!

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Think you must walk 54 yards to walk around your garden. How many feets is that?

Check that the 'Length' group is selected. If not, click on it.
The rightmost list shows now the units 'contained' in the 'Length' group (m, Km, cm and so on). Find the 'yd' unit and drag it into the left unit field. (Press the Left mouse button on it, let the button pressed and move the mouse to the field, release now the button).
Let's now set the right unit to 'ft':
Drag now the 'yd' item in the right unit field. Change now the value in the top left field (value field) to 54. You should see the top right field change to 162.
(If not, check that the current units are respectively yd and ft). Ok, the distance to walk is @{b}162 feet@{ub}.
You can try to do other conversions, like converting 463 m/s to knot, look in the Speed group [900] or 851 g to oz [about 30].

Do you wonder how to use the Prefixes list?
@{fg shine}·@{fg text} What about converting 20'000 Kyd (Kilo-yards) to mau (milli Astronomical Units)? ;-)

To use a prefix, you have to select the prefix in the prefixes list ('Original' if you don't want to change the prefix) and then drag the unit on the unit you want to change.

Click on the 'K (+3)' item of the prefixes list, and then drag the 'yd' unit (Length group) to the left unit field.
Click on the 'm (-3)' prefix and then drag the 'au' unit on the right unit field.
Change now the left value to 20000. Do you read @{b}0.12225...@{ub} in the top right field? Good, it's correct.

Let's try to combine some units:
@{fg shine}·@{fg text} If the speed of a car is 200 Dam/min (Dam is deca meter), how many miles per day (mi/d) does it do?

To create the Dam/min, I suggest to create Dam (Da+m) and then divide by min.
Let the current action to '='. Set the current prefix to 'Da (+1)' and put the 'm' unit in the left unit field.
You should now have 'Dam' in the left unit field. Because we now want to do a division, let's select the '÷' button. Go to the time group and drag 'min' on the left unit field.
Do you have 'Dam/min' in the left field? Great. Let's do the same to the right field.
Go back to the replace mode ( '=' ), select the Length group and put 'mi' in the right field. Set the current mode to division again ( '÷' ), go back to the Time group and drag the day (d) into the right unit field.
Now the units are ready, let's write the correct value: replace the left value by 200. You should read @{b}1789.549...@{ub} in the right value field. That car (assuming that it has infinite energy and that there is no others cars ;-) would do about 1800 miles every day..

Here is an example of an interesting use of combining units:
@{fg shine}·@{fg text} There is a big field, that is 800 yards wide and one kilometer long. How many hectares?

This is like doing 800 yd * 1 Km, that is like doing 800*1 yd*Km , that is 800 yd*Km.
Let's do it:Select the Length group, Replace mode and Original prefix. select Km in the list, then switch to Multiply mode and drag yd in the left unit field. you should have Km*yd.
put Ha in the right unit field (Area group) and write 800 in the left value field. The field's area is 73.152 Ha.

I'll now assume you know how to do a composed unit, I'll say you things like: 'set the left unit to Km*yd'.
Hint: If you know how the unit must be written, you can also write directely the unit into the field. Remember to press Return if you edit a unit!
Note that you can't put parhenthesis within others ones or put a parhenthesis to a power: ()^x and (...(...)...) aren't correctely read.

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} A last example: a wall must be repainted. It is two yards high and four meters wide. the paint must have two milimeters and the man that do it put 30 ml of paint every second. How long must he work?

This is a rather complicated problem. We must think a bit before doing it.
I suggest to first calculate the amount of paint used and then divide it by 30 ml/s:

The amount of paint: it is rather easy, just multiply 2 mm, 2 yd and 4 m to get it. Put mm*yd*m into the left unit field and write 16 in its value field. (2*2*4 is 16)
It is not required, but I think it is better to convert it into ml and to do the division. (If you don't mind having huge units, you can directely divide that by (ml/s) and convert it into minutes. If you do so, you don't have to what is written below, just check that your answer is the same than mine :-)
Otherwise, convert it into ml by putting 'ml' in the right field. You should get 14630.4 .
Warning: we will now work on that unit, so we have to make it the 'start' unit. Press the space bar or use the Switch @{"menu" link menus} item in the Tools menu. The title bar should now display [Right] instead of [Left].
Let's divide 14630.4 ml by 30 ml/s: We have to divide separately the unit and the value.
First, the unit: replace the 'ml' unit by 's'. (a more correct way to do it is to add '/(ml/s)' at the end of it, or you can also use the lists, divide by ml and multiply by s)
Note that if we had 'm^3' or 'l' or anything else than 'ml', We would be required to keep that unit. E.g. if we had m^3, we would have had 'm^3*s/ml'.
Then, the value: write 14630.4/30 in the right field. Note that you have to press return to have it calculated.
Replace the left unit by another time unit, I suggest minutes. You should now read 8.128 . If you want to know how many second are that '.128', simply remove the 8 before it, and read 7.68 seconds.
So the man that did it needed a bit more than eight minutes (plus 7.68 seconds to be exact)

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} A new question, but easier this time: Think you are at a place where the temperature is very low. You ask someone about it and he answers: it was nine degrees (farenheit) lower yesterday! You look a thermometer that displays: -10 °C. What displayed that thermometer the day before?

As I said, it's rather easy: just use the adding feature of convertor to do it:
Activate the 'No conversion' item of the tools menu, set the left unit to -10°C and the right one to 9°C.
Select now the 'substract' menu item. Beware that the current unit must be the @{u}left@{uu} one before doing that!
This will replace 10°C by -10°C-9°F, i.e. -15°C. Unset the 'No conversion' item to put Convertor back to its normal state.

Let's experiment the 'Tools' menu:

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Try to find the Si unit corresponding to 386 oz*N*yd/J
You should find about 10 Kg (10.006202322963 in fact)
If you don't managed, read that:
Put oz*N*yd/J in the left unit field.
Write 386 in the value field above it and select the 'Convert to Si' item of the tools menu. The unit and value are changed to the new value.

If you want to know the formula to convert a unit into an other, put a unit in a unit field, the other unit in the other field and set the unit you want to be converted (i.e. not the destination unit) to the start unit ([Left] or [Right]) and select the 'Show formula' menu item.
@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Try now to get the formula to convert a temperature in °C into °F.
You should get a requester that displays:

To convert Celsius° into Farhenheit°:
* Multiply by 1.8
* Add 32.

If you don't managed to do it (what? :) follow these rules:
1) Put °C in the left unit field and °F in the right unit field
2) set the current unit to [Left] if necessary.
3) Select the 'Show formula' menu item in the 'Tools' menu.
4) Read the requester that pops up

This feature is useful if you often need a specific conversion, so you don't have to rush to your Amiga (and you probably aren't always near your Amiga ;-)

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Imagine two cities that are separated by six miles (mi). It takes a car eight minutes to go from one city to the other (let's assume it's speed is constant).
Well, imagine now that the guy that drives this car wants to go faster. So he buys a new engine that goes ten kilometers per hour faster. How long does it take him now to go to the other city?

Just divide the distance (6 mi) by the speed (well, we'll find it later) and get the time.
And the speed is 6 mi divided by eight min plus ten Km/h.
To do an addition (or a substraction), first activate the 'No conversion' flag and then set the four field according to your calculation. The add menu item adds the two displayed units and puts the result in the current unit/value. You can then deactivate the flag.
Let's calculate the speed first: activate the 'no conversion' flag; put 0.75 mi/min in the left fields and 10 Km/h in the right ones.
Use now the 'Add' item to add these two values. Deactivate the 'no conversion' flag: we don't need it anymore. Divide now six by the value you found (Use the value that has mi/min as units!) and put the answer in the left field; replace now the mi/min by min (that is mi/(mi/min) ).
It takes him now seven minutes to him to go there... (Just hope he didn't pay too much for his engine ;-)

Well, are you ready to start the creation of new units? It is a very powerful and @{u}easy@{uu} feature of Convertor.

If you often need a composed unit, you can add it into a list:
@{fg shine}·@{fg text} For example: It can be useful to measure speeds in space in miles per second or Km per second. Let's create a new composed unit.
Choose one of the two units above (mi/s or Km/s) and put it in one of the two unit fields. Also select the group Speed (the units are speeds). Now put the mouse cursor over the @{u}frame@{uu} of that field, press the left mouse button and keep it pressed.
You should now see a second frame surrounding the field. Move the mouse around, without releasing the mouse. You can see now the field moving with the cursor. Put the field over the Units list, at the place you want your unit to be put (you will see a black and white line at that place).
When you're satisfied, release the button and you'll see your unit in the list. Congratulation, you created your first unit! You can now play with it, convert it int Km/h and so on.
E.g. :try to find out the speed of the Earth relative to the Sun. (Note: to the distance from Earth to Sun is one astronomical unit, 1 au and you can find the circumference of a circle doing the double of the ray and multiplying by pi (3.14159265358979)).
You should get 18.5080979476887 if you work with mi/s or 29.785896383525 if you used Km/s.

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} Second example: We want to compare the speed of other planets, comets or anything else to the speed of the Earth you found above. We could of course divide by the speed of the Earth every time, but wouldn't it be easier to have a complete unit representing Earth's speed?
We would get e.g. 1.1757 Espeed for Venus.
If you lose the result of the previous question (the speed of the Earth, no matter what unit), calculate it again. Drag now the @{u}value@{uu} of the speed ('29.785896383525' if you used Km/s) into any place of the Speed list (open it before starting dragging the value)
When you release the button, Convertor will ask you a name for the new base unit. Enter e.g. Espeed (or 'EarthSpeed' if you have enough room, or anything else, but take care to write a name that explains clearly what this unit represents).
(I will assume you wrote 'Espeed') You should now have an 'Espeed' item in the Unit list. Look in the Base group, you should also see an 'Espeed' item at the end. Great! You made a brand new base unit!
Let's play a bit with it.
I found the following values in an book: The mean distance from Venus to the Sun is 0.723332 astronomical units and it's 'year' (the time it needs to do a complete rotation around the Sun) is 224.701 of 'ours' days (days of the Earth, it's enough complicated so ;-).
Try to find the speed of Venus relative to the Sun in 'Espeed' unit. You should find about 1.1757 Espeed. It does mean that Venus goes about 1.1757 times faster than the Earth.

@{fg shine}·@{fg text} If you want to save these changes to disk, use the 'Save' menu item of the 'UnitData' menu.
You can play with the units without danger to lose the UnitData file on disk. But if you did something you want to keep , it's better to save UnitData. You can also easily keep several UnitDatas on disk, using the Save As and Load From items.

You can also sort units/groups, see the @{"menus" link menus} for more information about the UnitData menu.

Have fun with Convertor!

@endnode

@node "window" "User Interface"
@next "menus"
@prev "tour"
You can have a short help by keeping the mouse over a gadget. A Help bubble will then appear.
(note that the 'Help Bubbles' option of the help menu must be activated)

Here I explain the visual objects of Convertor. There is another page for the @{"menus" link menus}.

@{fg shine}The two top fields@{fg text} (default values one and one) are the values of the current units.
They are usually the 'question' and the 'answer'.
You can drag one (select the border of it) and drop it in the other to copy the value.
The @{u}current@{uu} value is indicated in the title bar ([Left] or [Right])
Note that you aren't required to put a value (like '12.4') but can put an expression (like '62/5').

These are the functions supported (Some might be useless for Convertor, I directely pumped the code from picFX, my picture maniplation program :):

+-*/^%       Classic infix operators. % is modulo.
abs          absolute value ( |x| )
acos         Arc cosine
asin         Arc sine
atan         Arc tangent
cos          Cosine (same arg as sine)
cosh         Hyperbolic cosine
ln           natural logarithm
log(b,x)     logarithm of x in base b
min,max      smaller, respectively bigger value from two args.
neg          negative
sin          Sine (expects argument in rad)
sinh         Hyperbolic sine
sqrt         squareroot
tan          Tangent ...
tanh         Hyperbolic tangent

An expression returns zero if there is a mistake.

@{fg shine}The two fields below@{fg text} (default values 'm' and 'm') are the current units.
They behave exactly like the above field (drag 'n' drop and so on)
You can change their values by using the lists on the bottom of the window but also by writing a new unit in it.
Be careful when using prefixes, if a unit of the same name exists, it will be used. (e.g. milli inches, if you write 'min', it will be understood as minute). To avoid that, put a '.' between the unit and the prefix (i.e. 'm.in').

@{fg shine}The Action buttons@{fg text} (× ÷ and =) are used to determine what will happen when you will click in the Units list (bottom right).
* If it is '×', activating a unit will multiply the current unit by the selected unit (e.g. if the current unit is 'm/s', and the mode is '×', a click on the 'm' unit will change the current unit to 'm^2/s'),with its prefix, see the prefix list.
* If it is '÷', activating a unit will divide the current unit by the selected unit (e.g. if the current unit is 'm^2/s', and the mode is '÷', a click on the 'm' unit will change the current unit to 'm/s')
* If it is '=', activating a unit will change the current unit to it. (e.g. if the current mode is '=' and you click on the 'm/s' unit, the current unit will always become 'm/s')

@{fg shine}The Accuracy slider@{fg text} (default position 14) sets the number of @{u}digits@{uu} displayed after a calculation. (e.g. 123.456789 with accuracy = 6 will become 123.457) use this if you want a rounded result, but only when you need the result (e.g. during the calculation, keep it to 14 and eventually lower it when you read the final answer).

@{fg shine}The Level difference switch@{fg text} is enabled only when the left and right units does not have the same zero (usually only temperature units, the °C and °F are not zero at the same temperature).
See @{"Level and difference units" link ld} to have more explanation about the effects of these buttons.

@{fg shine}The groups list@{fg text} (Length, Time and so on) Each item represent a group of composed units (except the 'Base' group, which lists each base unit, see below). They can be reordered by simply click on one, dragging it elsewhere in the list and dropping at the desired place (but note that Convertor prevents you from putting something after the special 'Base' group, which must remain the last).
When you click on one, it will become the current group, and all units in it will be displayed in the 'Units list' (see below).
You can delete, rename and create groups using the menus.

@{fg shine}The prefixes list@{fg text} (The second from the left) This is the list of the available prefixes.
When you click on a composed unit (The list on the right), the unit's prefix will be replaced by the one you selected unless the 'Original' item is selected in the list.
When the composed unit is made of more than one base unit, only the first's prefix will be changed (e.g. if the prefix is 'K' and you click on 'm/s', the unit will become 'Km/s').
Keep that list on 'Original' when you want the exact item in the 'Units list' to be used.

@{fg shine}The Units list@{fg text} (The third from the left) contains the list of available units in the current group.
See above to see what happens when you double click on an item.
This list can be sorted (like the groups list) using Drag'n'Drop. You can also drag an item into a unit field, which performs the same action that double clicking on an item.
Although note that when you double click on an unit, it will act on the @{u}current@{uu} unit.
(To change the destination unit, you either have to change the current group, which can cause problem because of automatic conversion, or use drag&drop)

You can add a new Unit by dragging a unit field in this list It will be added at the position of your mouse.
You can also create a new base unit by dragging a value field in this list. A requester will open to ask you the new name.
Read the @{"tour" link tour} to see some examples.

@endnode

@node "menus" "menus"
@next "Troubleshooting"
@prev "window"

@{b}MENU GENERAL@{ub}

About     (@{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}?)

This displays information about Convertor.

About MUI (@{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}')

This pops up the About Mui requester.

MUI Prefs (@{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}P)

Lets you change the local preferences for Convertor, like background pattern, font and so on. Please read the Mui documentation for more information about the settings.

@{fg shine}_________________________________@{fg text}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ
Hide      (@{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}Z)

Use this to hide Convertor. You can pop it up again by either clicking on its app-icon or using its short-key, depending what you set in the Mui Settings. You can also show it using Exchange.

Reset     (@{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}W)

Like quitting and starting again Convertor. UnitData is also reloaded.

Quit      (@{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}Q)

I do not really know what it does. Better not to use it ;-)

@{b}*******************************************@{ub}

@{b}MENU TOOLS@{ub}

Convert         (@{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}C)

Converts the current value into the other unit.
It should never be used, because Convertor converts automatically every time the answer may change (e.g. when you change the current value, or change the accuracy).
Note: When 'No Conversion' is activated, see below, you have to use this item to do a conversion.

UnDo            (@{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}K)

Restores units and values like they were before last operation. (So UnitData manipulation can't be cancelled)
the number of steps can be set using tooltypes: 'UNDOSTEPS=<number>'

ReDo            (@{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}R)

Performs again the operation you just undoed.

Convert to SI   (@{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}&)

Converts the current value to its SI equivalent. E.g. if you have four calories, you'll get 16.7472 Kg*m^2/s^2.

Inverse         (@{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}/)

Inverse the current value. If you have 5 m/s, you'll get 0.2 s/m.

Show formula    (@{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}=)

Shows the formula you can use to convert the current value's unit into the other. Example: you often need to convert Kelvins into Farhenreit degrees, so put °F in the right unit field and K in the left (check that left is the current value). Use this menu item and you will get: 'Multiply by 1.8 and substract 459.67'.

Switch          (@{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}S)

Like pressing the Space bar. Switches the current value

@{fg shine}_________________________________@{fg text}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ
  No conversion (@{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}B)

When this is activated, the automatic conversion feature of Convertor will be deactivated. (The only way to do a conversion is then to use the Convert menu-item). Useful if you want to do additions or substraction, see below.

Add             (@{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}+)

Add the current value to the answer. Example: if you want to add five feet to ten meters:
* deactivate automatic conversion.
* put five feet in the current field.
* put ten meters in the other field.
* Select the Add item in the Tools menu.
* Reactivate automatic conversion.

Substract       (@{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}-)

Like add, but a substraction (did you guess it? ;)
Be careful to not mistake the start and end value!
@{b}end-value gets end-value - start-value@{ub}

@{b}*******************************************@{ub}

@{b}MENU UNITDATA@{ub}

SI »
    Add SI      (S)

Use this to create a new SI type. The program will create a new base unit representing this SI type, and then a composed unit composed of this base unit.

BASE
    » Add       (B)

This will create a new base unit. It will have the same value than the current unit, e.g. you have 4.673 yd/h as the current unit, use 'Base:Add', the program will ask you for a name for your unit (enter 'NewSpeed'), so 1 NewSpeed will equal 3.673 yd/h.
Note that a base unit does not use the others base units you used (here:yd and h), so if you change their values or delete them, the new unit (here: 'NewSpeed') will stay the same.
If the current group isn't 'Base', this function will also create a new composed unit.
Convertor beeps you if you write an illegal name.

    » Delete    (Ctrl B)

This will delete the selected base unit. If the current groups isn't 'Base', the program will delete all base units used by the composed unit, after having asked you a confirmation.
Be careful if you use this feature with units like 'Oz*yd*in/(s*h)': You would delete the units Oz, yd, in, s AND h! It can however be useful if you created a base unit and a composed one at the same time, you can also delete both at the same time with this function.
Note that it is better to use 'Delete Composed' if you want to delete a base unit, see below to know why.

    » Set Zero  (Alt B)

Several units represent the same kind of unit (e.g. temperatures) but do not have the same zero. °F's zero is at 255.372222... and °C's one is at 273.15.
You can set this value using 'Set Zero'. It represents the conversion of 0 <Base unit to be changed> into <SI equivalent unit>.
If two units do not have the same zero and you want to convert from one of them into the other, you must set the '@{"Level difference switch" link ld}' to Level or Difference.

    » Full Name (Alt N)

Use this to set the full, human readable, name of your base unit (put it in plural). For instance, the full name of "ft" is "feet". This is currently only used by show Formula. Later versions will feature some information window for a given unit.

    » Rename    (Shift B)

Use this to rename the selected base unit. If the current group isn't 'Base', you can use this to change the unit. If you have e.g. 'Km/h' selected, use this function, write 'yd/s' and the unit will become yd/s. It is a fast way to delete the unit and create a new one.

COMPOSED
    » Add       (C)

This will create a new composed unit. It will in fact copy the current unit into the Units list. You can do the same if you drag a unit field into the list.
If the current group is 'Base', the program will ask you if you want to create a new base unit (because composed units can't be put into the 'Base' group), if you answer yes, the program will act exactely as if you used the 'Base:Add' menu item.

    » Delete    (Ctrl-C)

This will delete the selected composed unit in the units list.
If the current group is 'Base', the program will ask you if you want to delete all composed units using the selected base unit.
This is usually the best way, because if you delete a base unit using 'delete base', all composed units using that base unit won't work anymore (you will get that frightening INTERNAL FAILURE requester :-)
Note: when you delete the last unit of a group, this group also disappears.

GROUP
    » Add       (G)

This will create a new group of with the name of your choice. The current composed unit will be put in it. If it is not what you wanted, first create a new unit before deleting it, because a group must contain at least one composed unit.
Convertor beeps you if you write an illegal name.

    » Delete    (Ctrl-G)

This will delete the current group @{u}AND ALL CONTAINED COMPOSED UNITS!!@{uu}

    » Rename    (shift-G)

Use this to rename a group.

    » Sort groups (@{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}G)

Use this to sort the groups in alphabetical order.

SORT

This menu lets you sort the items of the units list ...

    » Alphabetically

... in alphabetical order

    » Numerically

... or in numerical order: the base units will be sorted by their factor (Zero value not used) and the composed units will be sorted by their total factor.

It can be useful to e.g. put the Time units from the shortest time to the longest, so you can find a unit faster.

    » Reverse

This reverses the order of the units, the last becomes the first and so on.

@{fg shine}_________________________________@{fg text}
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ
New       (@{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}N)

Use this to start a new empty UnitData. The program will ask you the name of the first group and the first unit in this group.

Load      (@{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}L)

Use this to reload the last saved UnitData (filename: 'currentdir:UnitData')
Only «Type4 CONVERTOR-UnitData» are read by Convertor 2.80.
So unitdata from v1.6 or older aren't read. But it doesn't matter, because all units of those
version are included in the current default unitdata.

Load From (@{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}O)

Like load, but you can select another filename.

Save      (@{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}S)

Use this to save the current UnitData in the default filename. It will be available when you start Convertor again.

Save As   (@{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}A)

Like Save, but you can select another filename. Load it with Load From.

About     (@{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}U)

Shows you some information about the current used UnitData.

@{b}*******************************************@{ub}

@{b}MENU HELP@{ub}

This menu displays some chapter of this guide.

Help Contents    (@{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}H)

The contents page of this guide

SI/base/composed (@{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}T)

The Si/base/composed page of this guide.

  Help Bubbles   (@{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}I)

Lets you activate «bubble help»: When activated, you can have a brief help about a gadget if you let the mouse over it.

@endnode
@node "Troubleshooting" "QTCBA / Troubleshooting"
@next "Thanks"
@prev "menus"
If you have a problem, first check the requirement list, and that you have correctly installed all files. If it is ok, read all this page, and if it doesn't help you, mail me.
Also read the '@{"bugs" link bugs}' page.

@{b}I converted 0 °C to °F and obtained 0 instead of 32. This must be a bug in Convertor.@{ub}

No this is not a bug. You simply put the level/difference switch to difference instead of level.

@{b}My computer has crashed with a guru as I used/started/quit convertor.@{ub}

This is probably a bug of Convertor. Send me the guru number (e.g. 8000 0003), how you produced it, and you configuration (memory, kickstart, workbench, mui version)

@{b} Convertor's window is locked (I can't resize it or it isn't redrawn when I resize it)!@{ub}

Like above, tell me how you produced it, your configuration (memory, kickstart, workbench, mui version)
Note that there is a bug that causes that is known: if you write an expression whose result is undefined or too big, Convertor locks up and eats all the processor until you hard remove it or reset :-(

@{b}What is QTCBA @{ub}?

Questions that could be asked. I first thought to put FAQ, but almost every question of this list has never been asked ;-)

@{b}Convertor says me it doesn't find UnitData (or any other file) @{ub}

- First check that the file is in the same directory than Convertor

- Then check you launched it from its directory. (see @{"Installation" link installation})

@{b}Convertor makes Enforcer hits!@{ub}

send me the output of Enforcer and how you produced the hit.

@{b}the multiply and/or divide gadgets (action) are empty (there isn't anything in them)@{ub}

Several fonts doesn't have those caracters ("×" and "÷"). Change your button (or default) font.

@{b}I found a problem that is not described above.@{ub}

Please tell me about it.

@endnode
