@node sbc "SI/base/composed units"
@prev mui
@next ld

There are three types of units in Convertor:
@{fg shine}SI units:@{fg text}
These are types of measure. Most are from the International System (SI).
All units are formed with these.
There are e.g. the @{u}Length@{uu}, the @{u}Time@{uu} and so on.
Speed isn't an SI unit because it can be formed with the above ones (a speed is a length divided by a time, e.g. Km per s)
I added some units that weren't from the 'official' SI units, because they caused problems with Convertor.
The @{u}Angles@{uu} are 'officially' a length divided by another, but Convertor would simplify it to a ratio.
Also memory is not in the 'real' SI units ;-)

@{fg shine}BASE units:@{fg text}
These are simple units that can be formed by one or more SI unit.
the list can be viewed by opening the 'Base' group.
They can't contain the '/', '*' or '^' caracters, you have to make a @{u}composed@{uu} unit to do that.
A base unit has also a factor. e.g. the @{u}yd@{uu} has factor 0.9144 and the @{u}ft@{uu} has a factor 0.3048, which is three times smaller. So converting between them will be like multiplying or dividing by three.
A base unit can have a different zero that the default one (see @{"level/difference units" link ld}).
It is possible to not use any SI types in a base unit, it would make a ratio (like '%')
You never manipulate base units but always composed units, see below.

@{fg shine}COMPOSED units:@{fg text}
This is simply several base units put together. The unit list on the right bottom of the window is made only by composed units (except if the current group is 'Base')
Its factor is entirely defined by the units that compose it.
You can have several base units of the same SI type in a single composed unit.
e.g. @{u}h/day@{uu} is the time you work every day.
But you aren't allowed to put twice the same unit in the same composed unit. (They are automatically simplified: m*m gets m^2)
You can have a composed unit without any base unit, it would be a simple ratio (1).

Each base units that compose a composed unit can also have a @{fg shine}PREFIX@{fg text}.

Remember that: @{u}composed units@{uu} are defined with @{u}base units@{uu}, that are defined with @{u}SI types@{uu}

@endnode
@node ld "Level/difference units"
@prev sbc
@next tour

If I ask you how many °F are the same than 5°C, what would you answer?

In fact, it can be either 41°F or 9°F.

If you look at a thermometer that shows the temperature in both units (°C and °F) you will see that 5°C is 41°F. So what is that 9°F?
Here is the answer: If the temperature @{u}raises@{uu} of five °C, it would be like if it had raised of nine °F.

So the first example was a comversion between two @{u}Difference@{uu} units and the second was between two @{u}Level@{uu} units.

Another example is the conversion of 0°C to °F: this is usually (@{u}level@{uu}) 32°F, but a @{u}difference@{uu} of zero °C is the same than zero °F !

When the temperature is in a more complicated (like 'K/s'), it is always a Level unit.
Also when you put a prefix (like 'mK'), which isn't often used, it will be fixed to a difference.
@endnode
